1.      Drag and drop Execute SQL Task from the SSIS Toolbox onto the canvas

2.      Configure the Execute SQL Task to initialize the staging table for Craigslist dataset by truncating all previous data by providing the T-SQL query and screenshot below:



Truncating Query:

IF EXISTS (SELECT * FROM SYS.objects WHERE NAME = 'CraigsListSTG' AND type = 'U')

DROP TABLE CraigsListSTG

GO

CREATE TABLE CraigsListSTG

               (

               id Nvarchar(20),

               url VARCHAR(200),

               region VARCHAR(50),

               regionUrl VARCHAR(200),

               price VARCHAR(50) NULL,

               [year] VARCHAR(50) NULL,

               manufacturer VARCHAR(50),

               model VARCHAR(50),

               condition VARCHAR(50),

               cylinder VARCHAR(50),

               fuel VARCHAR(50),

               odometer VARCHAR(50) NULL,

               titleStatus VARCHAR(50),

               transmission VARCHAR(50),

               vin VARCHAR(50),

               drive VARCHAR(50),

               size VARCHAR(50),

               vehicleType VARCHAR(50),

               paintColor VARCHAR(50),

               imageUrl VARCHAR(200),

               -- description VARCHAR(8000),

               -- county VARCHAR(50),

               state VARCHAR(50),

               lat VARCHAR(50) NULL,

               Long VARCHAR(50) NULL,

               FileDate Nvarchar(20),                   -- Introduced to help track audit files

               InsertDate Datetime default getdate()      --Introduced to help track ETL process

               )

4.      Use SSIS Script Task from SSIS Toolbox to display the JSON file being processed as per the screenshot below showing its configuration – (1) Provide variables to be used for File Path and File Name as created in variables function and (2) Edit C# Script as explained below:


Press Edit Script to get to C# Main Script to modify as per shaded yellow/green text:

 

#region Namespaces

using System;

using System.Data;

using Microsoft.SqlServer.Dts.Runtime;

using System.Windows.Forms;

using System.IO;

#endregion

 

            // TODO: Add your code here

 

            string strFilePath;     //FILEPATH SSIS variable

            string strFileName;     //FILENAME SSIS variable

 

            strFilePath = Dts.Variables["User::JSONFilePath"].Value.ToString();

            strFileName = Path.GetFileName(strFilePath);

            Dts.Variables["User::JSON_FileName"].Value = strFileName;

 

            MessageBox.Show(strFileName);

 

            Dts.TaskResult = (int)ScriptResults.Success;

             }

10.           Drag and drop Execute SQL Task from the SSIS Toolbox onto the canvas and rename it “Execute SQL Task-PopulateAuditFileLoadSTG”:

a.           Configure the Execute SQL Task to capture information about the JSON file being loaded – Count of records or vehicles loaded, File name, Processed By, whether archived or not, and Processed time. This is done by a pre-loaded stored procedure with two parameters (VehicleCount and FileName) embedded in the task in the SQL Command Tab:

o   EXECUTE uspAuditFileLoadSTG ?, ?

o   The stored procedure is part of the SQL Server scripts provided for preparing the Data Warehouse environment.

https://www.mssqltips.com/sqlservertip/5307/importing-json-files-using-sql-server-integration-services/

SQL Server Integration Services does not support JSON natively, so we need to develop a custom source for a data flow task to load JSON file. In this tip, I will walkthrough a method to develop a bespoke source to load JSON files using .Net libraries.
